POWASSAN VIRUS ENCEPHALITIS - USA (06): (NEW YORK)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 13 Jul 2017 10:35 am EDT
Source: Times Union [edited]
http://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Saratoga-County-resident-with-Powassan-virus-dies-11283838.php


A Saratoga County [New York] resident who was recently diagnosed with Powassan virus -- a rare but often fatal tick-borne disease -- has died, the state Department of Health said [Wed [12 Jul 2017].

State health officials would not say whether the person died of Powassan virus or had some other underlying illness or complication. Bryon Backenson, director of the State Health Department's Vector Surveillance Unit, cited patient confidentiality reasons.

The patient was likely exposed to Powassan virus in May and died in June [2017], Backenson said. The state will report the case to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention later this week.

A person can be infected with Powassan virus 15 minutes after being bitten by a tick that carries it. That's not much time to find and remove a tick and far quicker than the time it takes to transmit the more common Lyme disease; officials say it takes more than a day for a tick with Lyme to infect a person with that germ.

Yet Backenson stressed that New Yorkers should not panic over this single case of Powassan. The patient is the only person to contract the virus in New York so far this year [2017]. There have been 24 cases statewide since 2000, resulting in 5 deaths. One of those deaths was another Saratoga County resident in 2013.

By comparison, there are about 8000 reported cases of Lyme each year, and hundreds of cases each of other tick-born illnesses like anaplasmosis and babesiosis. Plus, Backenson said, New Yorkers get lots of tick bites that are no more than an annoyance.

"It's exceedingly rare," Backenson said of Powassan virus. "There's 30, 40, 50 000 tick bites that happen in New York every year, and the number that actually lead to cases of Powassan are one or 2, on average."

A study conducted several years ago by the Health Department and the Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies in Millbrook found a higher number of ticks than expected carried Powassan virus in the Hudson Valley, particularly east of the Hudson River, over a 5-year period ending 2012. In a study of 13 500 ticks, researchers found as many as 6 percent with the virus, depending on the county.

But Backenson said that has not translated into a big rise in Powassan virus [infections]. "It's not like we're seeing rapidly increasing numbers of Powassan [cases]," Backenson said. "It's one of the things that we see from time to time. It's very sad when someone ends up getting it."

Signs and symptoms of Powassan virus infection can include fever, headache, vomiting, weakness, confusion, seizures, and memory loss, according to CDC. Long-term neurological problems may occur.

There is no known treatment for the virus but people with severe cases may be hospitalized for breathing support, intravenous fluids, or medications to reduce brain swelling.

To reduce the risk of infection, health officials advise using tick repellents, wearing long sleeves and pants, avoiding bushy and wooded areas, and doing thorough tick checks after spending time outdoors.

[Byline: Emily Masters, Claire Hughes]

