[The state of New York can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5173571,35862. Saratoga County can be seen on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/new-york-county-map.gif. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ

In 2013, there were several cases of encephalitis caused by Powassan virus (POWV) infection in New York's lower Hudson Valley, and especially in Putnam County (see ProMED-mail posts listed below). A follow up study provided a good description of the tick virus vector and POWV relationship in the 2007-2012 period, and the prevalence of POWV in ticks during that time span (see Tick-borne encephalitis virus - USA: (NY) Powassan virus 20140823.2716624). There is no reason to think that the prevalence and geographic distribution of ticks and virus is restricted in New York state to the lower Hudson River Valley. Saratoga county is located in the upper Hudson River Valley.

As the report above mentions, the remarkable thing about POWV transmission by the deer tick (_Ixodes scapulars_) is the remarkably short feeding time required to transmit the virus. The rapid transmission of this virus by its vector is discussed in: Hermance ME, Thangamani S. Powassan Virus. An emerging arbovirus of public health concern in North America. Vector Borne Zoonotic Dis. 2017; 17(7); doi: 10.1089/vbz.2017.2110. [Epub ahead of print] http://online.liebertpub.com/doi/pdf/10.1089/vbz.2017.2110: "The duration of _Ixodes scapularis_, the deer tick, attachment required for successful transmission of Powassan virus to a host was found to be as little as 15 min by Ebel and Kramer (Ebel GD, Kramer LD. Short report: duration of tick attachment required for transmission of Powassan virus by deer ticks. Am J Trop Med Hyg 2004; 71(3): 268-71; https://www.researchgate.net/publication/8332784_Short_report_Duration_of_tick_attachment_required_for_transmission_of_Powassan_virus_by_deer_ticks) in 2004. This Ô¨Ånding was particularly striking because unlike other tickborne pathogens (_Borrelia burgdorferi_, _Babesia microti_, and _Anaplasma phagocytophilum_), very little time between tick attachment and virus transmission is needed. - Mod.TY]
